It is neatly executed, apparently by more than one hand 3 few contractions are employed, and the writ- ing is on the whole easy to read, exceptiug where it has been damaged by the fire. It has, however, been so severely burnt all round the edge, that nearly the whole of the margin is destroyed, and the beginnings of lines on the left, and ends of lines on the right hand pages, and sometimes a line or two at the tops of pages, are more or less illegible. The MS. thus injured has been re· paired or inlaid, the parts destroyed having been replaced by new parchment, so as to complete the original size of the pages, and to preserve the whole from further inj ury.
